-- 
India Stocks: Coal India, ITC, National Aluminium, ONGC

-- B y   A m e y a   K a r v e
-- 
2011-02-28T11:48:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-28/india-stocks-coal-india-itc-national-aluminium-ongc.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3:30 p.m. close in Mumbai.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose
122.49, or 0.7 percent, to 17823.4. The gauge fell 2.2 percent
this month, extending January’s 11 percent slide.  Auto stocks:  Mahindra & Mahindra Ltd . (MM IN), India’s
largest tractor and sport utility vehicle maker, gained 3.5
percent to 615.75 rupees and  Maruti Suzuki India Ltd . (MSIL IN),
the country’s biggest carmaker, added 3.4 percent to 1,208.2
rupees, after India proposed leaving excise duties unchanged in
its budget for the year from April.  Aviation stocks:  Kingfisher Airlines Ltd . (KAIR IN), the
nation’s second-biggest domestic carrier, fell 1.4 percent to
37.75 rupees and  SpiceJet Ltd . (SJET IN), a discount carrier,
dropped 4.8 percent to 38 rupees after Finance Minister Pranab Mukherjee proposed raising the service tax on air travel in his
budget speech today.  State-run refiners: Indian Oil Corp. (IOCL IN), the
nation’s largest refiner, advanced 2 percent to 298.95 rupees,
while Hindustan Petroleum Corp. (HPCL IN), the third-largest
state refiner, increased 2.6 percent to 320.30 rupees. Bharat
Petroleum Corp. (BPCL IN), the second-largest state-run refiner,
rose 2.7 percent to 553.45 rupees, after Mukherjee increased the
allocation for fuel subsidies more than 12-fold in the year
ending March.    Coal India Ltd . (COAL IN) surged 12 percent to 327.70
rupees, its best close since Dec. 15, after the world’s largest
producer of the fuel increased prices.    Hero Honda Motors Ltd . (HH IN), the biggest motorcycle
maker, declined 2.4 percent to 1,465.20 rupees. Hero Group’s
Hero Investments will raise 35 billion rupees ($773 million)
pledging its shares in Hero Honda Motors, the Economic Times
said, citing two people it didn’t identify. The money will be
used to pay for Honda Motor Co.’s stake in  Hero Honda , according
to the report.    ITC Ltd . (ITC IN), Asia’s second-largest cigarette maker by
market value, soared 8.1 percent to 169 rupees, its steepest
gain since May 2009, after Mukherjee proposed keeping excise
taxes on tobacco unchanged.    Lanco Infratech Ltd . (LANCI IN), an energy and
infrastructure company, added 2.7 percent to 38.15 rupees.
Griffin Coal Mining Co. creditors approved on Feb. 25 the
Australian mining company’s sale to Lanco Infratech, the
Australian newspaper reported.  National Aluminium Co. (NACL IN), one of India’s two
largest makers of the alloy, dropped 3.6 percent to 424.45
rupees. The Central Bureau of Investigation arrested A.K. Srivastava, the chairman of the state-run company, according to
the statement on the bureau’s website.  The mines ministry suspended Srivastava from his duties,
according to a statement on the Press Information Bureau’s
website. Calls to the mobile phone of Finance Director B.L. Bagra, who was appointed chairman and managing director of the
company yesterday, went unanswered.  Oil & Natural Gas Corp. (ONGC IN), India’s biggest
explorer, rose 3.2 percent to 270.35 rupees after Mukherjee said
in his budget speech that the government plans to sell 400
billion rupees of shares in state-owned enterprises in the next
financial year.  Separately, Royal Dutch Shell Plc is in talks with the
state-controlled explorer over a possible joint bid for Indian
offshore exploration licenses, the Times reported on Feb. 26,
citing a person it didn’t identify.    Reliance Power Ltd . (RPWR IN) gained 1.2 percent to 110.35
rupees. The generation arm of the Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group
will soon sign a power purchase agreement with the northern
state of  Uttar Pradesh  to sell 2,456 megawatts from the
company’s proposed plant in Madhya Pradesh, the Business
Standard reported, citing people it didn’t identify. A Reliance
Power spokesman declined to comment on the matter, the newspaper
said.  To contact the reporters on this story:
